column292: I would like to be a middle school teacher. In this position I would connect themes of history and english in order to motivate students to learn. This is an important stage in a pre-teen's life and they should have good teachers so that they can succeed in high school. Since coming to Stanford I have learned a great deal about the issues in the US education system and I see myself doing well in a teaching position, especially for minority students.
column316: having met people from all over the world I identify easily with all culture.

column292: My ideal position would pay me well and have flexible hours so I can come in whenever I want. The work environment would be non-hostile, rather collaborative and communicative. I would love to have older women already working there that would be open to being my mentor and helping me along, instead of feeling like I have competition. Ideally, this position would help me learn very interesting things that I could take away and apply to the rest of my life.

My ideal position in a new job would be in public relations, but also in a company that has to do with humor. Ideally, I would like a job that requires my particular skill set and allows them to have impact in an area that I care about. And if I end up being told to fulfill duties, then I would like some freedom as to how to engage in it.

My ideal position is a research internship involving the intersection of biology and computation. I find biology deeply fascinating and would like to use the skills I've learned as a computer science student to address important biological questions. I hope an internship in this field will allow me to better understand what it's like to be in computational biology, and that I will be able to further my passion for studying biological problems.

My ideal position would be a designer for a company that creates products related to neuroscience or cognitive science, preferably products that solve some sort of relevant problem in society. I enjoy the act of creating things and having something to show for my labor, and the opportunity to make a difference in the world through a material object spawned from my own hands brings me excitement and fulfillment. While I am extremely interested in the brain, I also would love to hone my creativity skills, and the mix between the technical and artistic side provides a well-rounded career that I could see myself delving into.

Video game developer/programmer. Preferably somewhere in the graphics division, or the user interface division. I'd love to make art for a living, but I also love the complexity and challenge of programming so combining the two would be ideal. My ideal position would include working in the business and managerial division of an aviation company. Furthermore, I've accumulated a multitude of experience working and interacting with various people, so I feel that a business position would allow me to further hone my collaborative skill set. Through collective discourse and teamwork, I am able to share my past experiences while learning from others at the same time.

My ideal job is more arbitrary than concrete. I can't say for certain that I want any specific position in a specific industry. My path is still uncertain. However, what I do know for certain are the circumstances of my job. For one, the job or internship position must have opportunity for growth. Without any window towards the future, I lack the motivation and incentive to surpass the mediocre. Furthermore, my job should be stable. Being slightly meticulous, I like working towards a single vision without having to worry about losing what I have already achieved - in this case, my job. Although, I believe, a job should be most importantly a passion or strong interest of mine, I don't want to lose sight of the monetary aspect of working. Without money, I won't be able to enjoy the aspects of life outside the workplace. Hence, I'd prefer lucrative over not.

I am not sure what my ideal job or internship would be. I would like to be able to work with other people, but also have my own creative independence.

column292: I would love to have a position that would allow me to do creative work. Specifically, creating fictional worlds and narratives as well as performing in them. I like to do a lot of hands on work rather than sitting at a desk, keeping to myself.

In that regard, I would really enjoy doing something that helped me to get a feel for the work I intend to do, and that would help me to further my future goals. My ideal position would be a job in a counseling office because I truly believe in the power of an ear to listen. As much as I value learning and knowledge, I believe that helping other adds a layer of meaning to work that makes it truly rewarding. Mental health issues in particular seem to be especially painful to experience. Because there is so little known about the brain during disorders like depression, it is difficult to effectively treat patients, and I would like to help others suffering from self-destructive thoughts and feelings to the best of my ability. I think caring for others in a time of need and helping to analyze people's circumstances has an extremely therapeutic and healing value. Further, I feel personally compelled to help others in their time of need, given prior experiences with emotional hardship in my own life and mental health issues among family members. I would hope that, through the job, I could provide support to others so that they can work through any issues they may have.

My ideal internship would be working with a doctor at a hospital because I'd like to pursue a medical career. I am planning on majoring in Human Biology in Stanford and then applying to medical school. Having working experience would be beneficial to my career and getting into graduate school.

Therefore, I am also interested in understanding more about psychology, especially certain mental illnesses such as depression. I am currently looking into clinical psychology, so any experience in psychology may help me understand this field and allow me to see and to develop my interest.

My ideal position would be as an average worker within a larger organization, preferably one that has to do with health care. I am intrigued by the human condition and the forces/causes that drive our behaviors as well as those that cause deleterious results in our health. I do not want to start off with much power considering I will be new to the organization, and it takes time and determination to gain the respect that those in charge deserve to have. Simultaneously, I do not want a low level position because of my strong education background. As of now, my ideal position would be to serve as an undergraduate research assistant at Stanford. Also, my goal is to attend graduate school after my four years at Stanford, and to ultimately get a Ph.D. Thus, I would love to start research as soon as I can.

Through research, I would be able to come up with new ideas and test theories when I encountered a problem without an obvious solution or a situation that didn't make sense to me. I would expect that my job would occasionally bring disappointments and obstacles that I could not overcome under pressure, and I would use those scenarios to learn what I could do better in the future. My ideal job would be an exciting position where I could serve my community and always learn more about myself, others, and the world around me.

column292: I don't know specifically, but my ideal position would apply psychological principles to another discipline in some way.  For example, I would like to work in behavioral economics (applying psychology to model market trends or consumer behavior) or in marketing.  I suppose my dream job would be to work in marketing for Coca-Cola.  More generally, my ideal position would be one in which I could have social interaction, but most of my projects were independent.  I like to talk to other people and discuss ideas, but I am more productive when I can focus on my own and am not dependent on others for parts of the project.

I would like to work in the field of psycho-linguistics, studying how people think and learn via studying how people learn and use language. I don't believe that we can get the full picture of the effects of learning a specific language in a pure laboratory setting, where we control the variables. I believe language is a cultural construct as much as it is a useful tool for communication. So to truly understand the differences and complexities of the effects of language on a developing brain we also have to examine the values of that culture that, I believe, are engrained along with that language. Therefore, my ideal position would be working in at a company or in a 'lab' that studies such things. Alternatively, my other ideal position would be working for the National Geographic show Brain Games, which takes a look at how the brain works and explains it in laymen's terms as an entertaining and educational show for just about all ages.

My ideal position is working with a legal team at either an art gallery or auction house. I am very interested in contract law as it applies to the fine art world. I would love to work with the sales/acquisitions department of a museum to ensure all sales/trades are contracted correctly.

Right now, because of my other commitments (academics and the Harmonics), I want a job which is amenable to my schedule. I used to think I wanted a job which did not demand much of my mental capacity, but in recent weeks I have begun to think that I would be okay with taking a job for which I needed to be mentally present.  /          In the future, when my job and my family become my primary commitments, my criteria will change somewhat. The job now does not need to be as "juggle-able," with other things in my life; however, things like time off and the ability to spend time with my family and any hobbies would become more important. I want to leave the office when my shift ends, and want the ability to take time off.

My ideal position is one where I actively engage with other people and apply my knowledge every day. Busy work can be ok sometimes, but applying what I learned in a new setting is what keeps me driven and focused on a task at hand. Furthermore, people are much more exciting than computers and everyone always has a good story to tell. These are a few of the reasons I desire to work as a physical therapist when I am older.

I want to work in an industry that is just as cutthroat as it is exciting. I want to be in a position that forces me to make tough decisions. I want to be able to have a change in scenery every once in a while. I want to be working on multiple projects at once. I want to be in a position where people respect me. I want to lead and follow. I want to learn. I want people to criticize me. I want a stimulating job. I want to work in Hollywood.

My ideal job is one in which I can actively participate in critical tasks, rather than slavishly doing the menial work. I would also get paid. I would also get to use my writing skills. But honestly I don't really want a job or internship in the traditional sense.

Raising a dog, a bearded dragon, a python, and a plethora of rodents and chickens has only increased my desire to understand the complexities of the animal mind. As a child, I was deeply entranced by human animal relationships.  My sister, who suffers from Asperger’s, was not able to make personal relationships easily and struggled severely in social settings. At school, I would push her to communicate, but the walls stayed up, only to be broken when we got back home and she melted into the pudgy golden fat rolls of our dog Max.  The only time she felt a sense of companionship was when she was with that golden-coated mutt.  Watching my sister feel a social connection because of her dog compelled me to find my own connection with animals and the world around them and me.  When I reached the age of earning my own dog, an even messier mutt named Ruby, I was ready to spend every minute with her.  I find my deepest joy when her and I master a new trick, and find my deepest sorrow when I realize I will be living without her this upcoming year. In my opinion, people greatly underestimate the power of human-animal connections.  I have discovered so much about myself through my connections with animals and I want to give that incredible discovery to those around me.  Animals are deeply underestimated and their ability to alter human attitude and happiness is incomparable to any other force. Hopefully a deeper knowledge of animal behavior could lead to better treatment of animals both in commercial and laboratorial settings.  Although I have gotten first hand experience with as many animals as possible, I have never had the opportunity to actually learn the science behind animal behavior.  The fact that animal behavioral courses are even offered excites me greatly. I am in the right place to expand both my interest and my knowledge. Due to this, I would love an internship working with behavioral scientists or working on animal research.
